I'm a professional anthrolinguist. You have to understand that the architecture of the mouth and nasal chamber is going to influence the types of sounds that anthros can make. This is why so many canid languages have glottal stops, fricative consonants, an overrepresentation of "r" and an emphasis on the vowels "a, o, u". It's also why every wolf name is "Rooja" or "Athora" or "Owara".
It's easier for them to make certain sounds. The "m, n" sounds aren't as easy when your lips are fitted over a muzzle, and sounds like "ee" in English will usually be approximated with a soft whine.
